# Learning Materials

## Overview

This page provides a list of educational resources to help you get started with the concepts covered in the Capture The Flag (CTF) challenges. Whether you're a beginner or have experience in cybersecurity, these resources will help deepen your understanding of key topics such as networking, web security, cryptography, and more.

## Recommended Resources

### 1. Networking Basics
- **Book**: *Computer Networking: A Top-Down Approach* by James Kurose & Keith Ross
  - This book provides a comprehensive introduction to computer networks and networking protocols.
- **Video**: [Introduction to Networking](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3QhU9jd03a8) on YouTube
  - A beginner-friendly video that covers the basics of networking and IP addressing.

### 2. Web Security
- **Tutorial**: [OWASP Web Security Testing Guide](https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/)
  - The OWASP guide provides detailed explanations and best practices for identifying web vulnerabilities like SQL injection and cross-site scripting.
- **Video**: [Web Security Fundamentals](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Qy4hpvFoyL4)
  - A video that introduces key web security concepts and attacks.

### 3. Cryptography
- **Article**: [Understanding Cryptography](https://www.springer.com/gp/book/9783642086334) - A great starting point for learning about encryption algorithms and security protocols.
- **Video**: [Cryptography Basics](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=06xPqUQn4e8)
  - A clear explanation of symmetric and asymmetric cryptography.

### 4. CTF-Specific Resources
- **CTF Learning Platform**: [OverTheWire](https://overthewire.org/wargames/)
  - A platform offering CTF challenges for beginners to advanced levels, helping you hone your cybersecurity skills.
- **CTF Guide**: [How to Solve CTF Challenges](https://www.hackingarticles.in/how-to-solve-ctf-challenges/)
  - This article explains various techniques and tools that can help you solve common CTF challenges.

## Additional Resources
If you need further reading or learning materials on specific topics, feel free to explore additional resources or ask your instructor for more suggestions.

